<div type="definition">
<p>CAUSE to REACT.</p>
    </div>
<div type="notes">
<div type="old-chinese-criteria">
<p>1. The current general word for stimulating a sentient being into action, or causing feelings, is gǎn 感 (ant. yìng 應 "respond").</p>
<p>2. Jī 激 refers to prodding something or someone into action.</p>
<p>3. Dòng 動 refers to bringing about action or movement in someone or something.</p>
<p>4. Kāng kǎi 慷慨 is marginal in this group and refers to a tendency to be moved into actions and feelings by other things.</p>
        </div>
<div type="modern-chinese-criteria">
<p>感動</p>
<p>激發</p>
<p>打動</p>
<p>激</p>
<p>激動</p>
<p>動容</p>
<p>感觸</p>
<p>棖觸</p>
<p>刺激</p>
<p>激勵</p>
<p>使興奮</p>
<p>使有生气</p>
<p>百感叢生</p>
<p>勖 (lit, obs) refers to encouraging or prompting something, and the word is marginal in the series.</p>
<p>感</p>
<p>觸</p>
<p>rough draft to BEGIN TO identify synonym group members for analysis, based on CL etc. 18.11.2003. CH ／</p>
        </div>
